				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \underline {\widehat{n}} $$\end{document}, with respect to the SSB [69]. These are the key pulsar timing elements that enable positioning of the spacecraft in the direction of a given pulsar.Fig. 1
A simplified approach for measuring the position of a spacecraft in the direction of a pulsar. The dashed lines represent a given pulse phase of a signal from the pulsar arriving at the true spacecraft position and an initial estimated position at two instants in time separated by an interval Δt. The ‘delta-correction’ is shown as n^¯⋅Δr¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
